 ENDF/B-VI MOD 4 Evaluation, August 1997, M.B. Chadwick and        725 1451
           P.G. Young (LANL)                                       725 1451
                                                                   725 1451
 Los Alamos LA150 Library, produced with FKK/GNASH/GSCAN code      725 1451
   in cooperation with ECN Petten.                                 725 1451
                                                                   725 1451
   This evaluation provides a complete representation of the       725 1451
 nuclear data needed for transport, damage, heating,               725 1451
 radioactivity, and shielding applications over the incident       725 1451
 neutron energy range from 1.0E-11 to 150 MeV.  The discussion     725 1451
 here is divided into the region below and above 20 MeV.           725 1451
                                                                   725 1451
 INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES < 20 MeV                                725 1451
   Below 20 MeV the evaluation is based completely on the ENDF/B-  725 1451
 VI.3 (Release 3) evaluation by P. G. Young, G. M. Hale, and M.    725 1451
 B. Chadwick [Yo94].                                               725 1451
                                                                   725 1451
 INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES > 20 MeV                                725 1451
   The ENDF/B-VI Release 3 evaluation of n + 14N data extends to   725 1451
 40 MeV and includes cross sections and energy-angle data for all  725 1451
 significant reactions.  The present evaluation utilizes a more    725 1451
 compact composite reaction spectrum representation of the data    725 1451
 above 20 MeV in order to reduce the length of the file, and we    725 1451
 have only included the ENDF/B-VI data below 20 MeV. To avoid      725 1451
 redundancy, the sections MT=78-90 are removed, since their        725 1451
 thresholds lie between 20 and 40 MeV. No essential data for       725 1451
 applications is lost with our representation above 20 MeV.        725 1451
   The evaluation above 20 MeV utilizes MF=6, MT=5 to represent    725 1451
 all reaction data.  Production cross sections and emission        725 1451
 spectra are given for neutrons, protons, deuterons, tritons,      725 1451
 alpha particles, gamma rays, and all residual nuclides produced   725 1451
 (A>5) in the reaction chains. To summarize, the ENDF sections     725 1451
 with non-zero data above En = 20 MeV are:                         725 1451
                                                                   725 1451
  MF=3 MT=  1  Total Cross Section                                 725 1451
       MT=  2  Elastic Scattering Cross Section                    725 1451
       MT=  3  Nonelastic Cross Section                            725 1451
       MT=  5  Sum of Binary (n,n') and (n,x) Reactions            725 1451
                                                                   725 1451
  MF=4 MT=  2  Elastic Angular Distributions                       725 1451
                                                                   725 1451
  MF=6 MT=  5  Production Cross Sections and Energy-Angle          725 1451
               Distributions for Emission Neutrons, Protons,       725 1451
               Deuterons, Tritons, and Alphas; and Angle-          725 1451
               Integrated Spectra for Gamma Rays and Residual      725 1451
               Nuclei That Are Stable Against Particle Emission    725 1451
                                                                   725 1451
   The evaluation is based on nuclear model calculations that have 725 1451
 been benchmarked to experimental data, especially for n + 14N     725 1451
 and p + 14N reactions [Ch97]. We use the GNASH code system        725 1451
 [Yo92], which utilizes Hauser-Feshbach statistical,               725 1451
 preequilibrium and direct-reaction theories. Spherical optical    725 1451
 model calculations are used to obtain particle transmission       725 1451
 coefficients for the Hauser-Feshbach calculations, as well as     725 1451
 for the elastic neutron angular distributions.                    725 1451
   Cross sections and spectra for producing individual residual    725 1451
 nuclei are included for reactions. The energy-angle-correlations  725 1451
 for all outgoing particles are based on Kalbach systematics       725 1451
 [Ka88].                                                           725 1451
   A model was developed to calculate the energy distributions of  725 1451
 all recoil nuclei in the GNASH calculations [Ch96]. The recoil    725 1451
 energy distributions are represented in the laboratory system in  725 1451
 MT=5, MF=6, and are given as isotropic in the lab system. All     725 1451
 other data in MT=5,MF=6 are given in the center-of-mass system.   725 1451
 This method of representation utilizes the LCT=3 option approved  725 1451
 at the November, 1996, CSEWG meeting.                             725 1451
   Preequilibrium corrections were performed in the course of the  725 1451
 GNASH calculations using the exciton model of Kalbach [Ka77],     725 1451
 [Ka85], validated by comparison with calculations using Feshbach, 725 1451
 Kerman, Koonin (FKK) theory [Ch93].  Discrete level data from     725 1451
 nuclear data sheets were matched to continuum level densities     725 1451
 using the formulation of Ignatyuk [Ig75] and pairing and shell    725 1451
 parameters from the Cook [Co67] analysis. Neutron and charged-    725 1451
 particle transmission coefficients were obtained from the         725 1451
 optical potentials, as discussed below.  Gamma-ray transmission   725 1451
 coefficients were calculated using the Kopecky-Uhl model [Ko90].  725 1451
                                                                   725 1451
 DETAILS OF THE n + 14N ANALYSIS                                   725 1451
   GNASH calculations [Yo92,Ch94] were performed for neutron and   725 1451
 proton reactions on nitrogen up to 150 MeV, and the calculated    725 1451
 results were benchmarked against experimental data. For neutrons  725 1451
 below 100 MeV, the present evaluation made extensive use of our   725 1451
 previous work [Ch96a].  Very minor differences with this earlier  725 1451
 work exist due to recent developments in the GNASH code. Much use 725 1451
 was made of measured data in the evaluation, since an accurate    725 1451
 modeling of reactions on a light nucleus is difficult. In this    725 1451
 way we were able to obtain a fairly good description of the       725 1451
 emission spectra of secondary particles and gamma rays.           725 1451
 Additionally, the (angle-integrated) emission spectra of heavy    725 1451
 recoils were calculated using our model described in Ref. [Ch96]. 725 1451
 Some additional information on this evaluation can be found in    725 1451
 Ref. [Ch97].                                                      725 1451
   Between 20 and 150 MeV, the optical models used (the neutron    725 1451
 potential of Islam below 60 MeV [Is88]; Madland's potential       725 1451
 [Ma88] at higher energies, with Lane transformations for the      725 1451
 proton potential) provided a reasonably good description of       725 1451
 measured reaction cross section data. But since a very accurate   725 1451
 description of the reaction cross section is important for        725 1451
 determining secondary particle spectra, we slightly modify the    725 1451
 calculated results to better describe the experimental data, and  725 1451
 renormalize the calculated transmission coefficients accordingly. 725 1451
 The SCAT2 code [Be92] was used to calculate the transmission      725 1451
 coefficients. No measurements for the neutron reaction cross      725 1451
 section on nitrogen exist above about 50 MeV. However,            725 1451
 systematics have been determined from a number of target elements 725 1451
 at 95 MeV by DeJuren [De50], and for 100 MeV protons by Kirby and 725 1451
 Link [Ki66] (at this energy the proton and neutron reaction cross 725 1451
 sections would be expected to be very similar). We have,          725 1451
 therefore, used these systematics to guide our evaluated reaction 725 1451
 cross sections. Additionally, below 50 MeV we have also been      725 1451
 guided by the proton-induced reaction cross sections of Carlson   725 1451
 et al. [Ca75]. Experimental total elastic scattering values of    725 1451
 Islam et al. [Is88], Olsson et al. [Ol90], and Petler et al.      725 1451
 [Pe85] were obtained by subtracting their angle-integrated        725 1451
 elastic data from the evaluated total cross sections (see below). 725 1451
 The evaluated total cross section was obtained by slightly        725 1451
 modifying the optical model results to agree with data,           725 1451
 principally the new high-accuracy results of Finlay et al.        725 1451
 [Fi93]. We use the ENDF/B-VI total cross section below 40 MeV     725 1451
 recently evaluated by Young [Yo94].                               725 1451
   Preequilibrium spectra for incident energies below 100 MeV were 725 1451
 taken from our previous work [Ch96], where they were evaluated    725 1451
 from a combination of FKK calculations [Ch93], and measured       725 1451
 emission spectra data, while ensuring that unitarity is conserved 725 1451
 (i.e., making sure the sum of primary emitted preequilibrium      725 1451
 spectra does not exceed the reaction cross section). This         725 1451
 approach has the advantage of facilitating a good representation  725 1451
 of emission spectra experimental data. However, the lack of such  725 1451
 data above 100 MeV prohibits its extension to higher energies,    725 1451
 and therefore above 100 MeV, exciton model calculations were      725 1451
 utilized from the GNASH code [Ka77, Ka85]. This results in some   725 1451
 (small) discontinuities around 100 MeV in the production cross    725 1451
 sections, though the impact of this is negligible for most        725 1451
 applications.                                                     725 1451
   Nuclear level densities were determined using the Ignatyuk      725 1451
 model [Ig75], as implemented by Arthur et al. [Yo92].  Pairing    725 1451
 energies were obtained from the Cook systematics with the Los     725 1451
 Alamos extensions to light nuclei from [Ar83].  This continuum    725 1451
 level density formulation is matched continuously onto discrete   725 1451
 low-lying levels at the lower excitation energies. Discrete level 725 1451
 information (energy, spin, parity, gamma-ray branching ratios) is 725 1451
 tabulated for each nuclide in an input file, which is based on    725 1451
 the Ajzenberg-Selove compilations.  For each nucleus we performed 725 1451
 a level-density analysis and determined the excitation energy at  725 1451
 which we judged the level data complete. Gamma-ray transmission   725 1451
 coefficients were obtained from the Kopecky-Uhl model [Ko90].     725 1451
   An important test of the accuracy of the data libraries is that 725 1451
 the evaluated emission spectra of light particles (A < 5) should  725 1451
 be consistent with the measurements by Subramanian et al.  of UC- 725 1451
 Davis [Su86].  We have compared our calculated (lab frame) angle- 725 1451
 integrated emission spectra of protons, deuterons, and alphas,    725 1451
 with these measurements, with good agreement. The structure seen  725 1451
 at high emission energies is due to the inclusion of discrete     725 1451
 nuclear levels in our calculations. Also, kerma factors obtained  725 1451
 from the evaluated cross sections are in fairly good agreement    725 1451
 with experimental data [Ch96].                                    725 1451
